{"key":"post-13106420","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13106420</id>\n<content>You don't heat fruiting chambers.&amp;nbsp; If necessary, heat the room they're in.&amp;nbsp; However, 55F to 60F at night and 70F or so during the day is fine.&amp;nbsp; You also don't need to fan out a shotgun terrarium.&amp;nbsp; It's always a good idea to wave the lid back and forth over the cakes after misting, but many growers don't and it still works fine.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I refuse to use the term &quot;set it and forget it&quot; because that's dumb.&amp;nbsp; However, lots of people do their shotgun terrariums that way and they still get fruits.&amp;nbsp; However, if air is exchanging properly, you'll need to mist to prevent the cakes from drying out.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To put things in perspective, I live in a high elevation mountain climate, where it gets down in the 30s at night, even in July/August when it gets into the 80s during the day.&amp;nbsp; I sleep with the windows wide open and under a heavy wool blanket to stay warm.&amp;nbsp; Terrariums on tables do great.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms love that day/night temp fluctuation.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13106421</next>\n<prev>13106384</prev>\n<first>13105508</first>\n<last>13108909</last>\n<when>1282865943</when>\n<utime>08/27/10 02:39 AM</utime>\n</post>"}